e Minister cannot open his answer with a direct attack on the member asking the question. [<em>Interruption</em>]</p><p class="Interjection"><strong>Mr SPEAKER</strong>: Order! [<em>Interruption</em>] Order! The member—[Interruption] Order! Iain Lees-Galloway, resume your seat. When I consider the tone of the question, I do not consider that there is anything out of order in the way the Minister started the question.</p><h4 class="QSubjectheadingalone"><strong>Point of Order—</strong><strong>Simultaneous Interpretation, Headsets</strong></h4><p class="Speech"><a name="time_20160705 15:17:54" ></a><strong>CHRIS HIPKINS (Senior Whip—Labour)</strong>: I raise a point of order, Mr Speaker. It is actually just a point of order of logistics. This being Māori Language Week I am sure members who are able to will be using Te Reo Māori. I notice that around the House a number of headsets that assist those of us who are not fluent Te Reo Māori speakers are missing, and therefore we have not been able to follow the debate. I wonder whether that can be addressed before the next time we have question time so that we can all follow along if we are not fluent Te Reo Māori speakers.</p><p class="Speech"><a name="time_20160705 15:18:20" ></a><strong>Mr SPEAKER</strong>: I will guarantee to the member that I will have that addressed before question time tomorrow. I apologise that it has been inadequate because of that.</p><p class="QOAEnd"><a name="time_20160705 15:18:30 " ></a><strong> </strong></p></div></body>
